<P>Screeching tires. Searching lights. Wailing sirens. Police cars =
everywhere.=20
Trisha Quickfinger did it again! Stealing the `Mona Lisa' had been more=20
difficult than planned, but being the world's best art thief means =
expecting the=20
unexpected. So here she is, the wrapped frame tucked firmly under her =
arm,=20
running to catch the northbound metro to Charles-de-Gaulle airport.=20
<P>But even more important than actually stealing the painting is to =
shake off=20
the police that will soon be following her. Trisha's plan is simple: for =
several=20
days she will be flying from one city to another, making one flight per =
day.=20
When she is reasonably sure that the police has lost her trail, she will =
fly to=20
Atlanta and meet her `customer' (known only as Mr. P.) to deliver the =
painting.=20
<P>Her plan is complicated by the fact that nowadays, even when you are =
stealing=20
expensive art, you have to watch your spending budget. Trisha therefore =
wants to=20
spend the least money possible on her escape flights. This is not easy, =
since=20
airlines prices and flight availability vary from day to day. The price =
and=20
availability of an airline connection depends on the two cities involved =
and the=20
day of travel. Every pair of cities has a `flight schedule' which =
repeats every=20
few days. The length of the period may be different for each pair of =
cities and=20
for each direction.=20
<P>Although Trisha is a good at stealing paintings, she easily gets =
confused=20
when booking airline flights. This is where you come in.=20
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A=20
name=3DSECTION0001001000000000000000>Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2>The =
input file=20
contains the descriptions of several scenarios in which Trisha tries to =
escape.=20
Every description starts with a line containing two integers <I>n</I> =
and=20
<I>k</I>. <I>n</I> is the number of cities through which Trisha's escape =
may=20
take her, and <I>k</I> is the number of flights she will take. The =
cities are=20
numbered <!-- MATH: $1, 2, \dots, n$ --><IMG border=3D0 alt=3D"$1, 2, =
\dots, n$"=20
align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX01.522/590i=
mg1.gif"=20
width=3D79 height=3D30>, where 1 is Paris, her starting point, and =
<I>n</I> is=20
Atlanta, her final destination. The numbers will satisfy <!-- MATH: $2 =
\le=9F n \le=9F 10$ --><IMG border=3D0 alt=3D"$2 \le=9F n \le=9F 10$"=20
align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX01.522/590i=
mg2.gif"=20
width=3D88 height=3D30> and <!-- MATH: $1 \le=9F k \le=9F 1000$ --><IMG =
border=3D0=20
alt=3D"$1 \le=9F k \le=9F 1000$" align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX01.522/590i=
mg3.gif"=20
width=3D104 height=3D32>.=20
<P>Next you are given <I>n</I>(<I>n</I> - 1) flight schedules, one per =
line,=20
describing the connection between every possible pair of cities. The =
first=20
<I>n</I> - 1 flight schedules correspond to the flights from city 1 to =
all other=20
cities ( <!-- MATH: $2, 3, \dots, n$ --><IMG border=3D0 alt=3D"$2, 3, =
\dots, n$"=20
align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX01.522/590i=
mg4.gif"=20
width=3D79 height=3D30>), the next <I>n</I> - 1 lines to those from city =
2 to all=20
others ( <!-- MATH: $1, 3, 4, \dots, n$ --><IMG border=3D0=20
alt=3D"$1, 3, 4, \dots, n$" align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX01.522/590i=
mg5.gif"=20
width=3D95 height=3D30>), and so on.=20
<P>The description of the flight schedule itself starts with an integer=20
<I>d</I>, the length of the period in days, with <!-- MATH: $1 \le=9F d =
\le=9F 30$ --><IMG border=3D0 alt=3D"$1 \le=9F d \le=9F 30$"=20
align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX01.522/590i=
mg6.gif"=20
width=3D86 height=3D32>. Following this are <I>d</I> non-negative =
integers,=20
representing the cost of the flight between the two cities on days <!-- =
MATH: $1, 2, \dots, d$ --><IMG border=3D0 alt=3D"$1, 2, \dots, d$" =
align=3Dmiddle=20
src=3D"file:///C:/Users/WU%20YONGHUI/AppData/Local/Temp/Rar$EX01.522/590i=
mg7.gif"=20
width=3D77 height=3D32>. A cost of 0 means that there is no flight =
between the two=20
cities on that day.=20
<P>So, for example, the flight schedule ``<TT>3 75 0 80</TT>'' means =
that on the=20
first day the flight costs 75, on the second day there is no flight, on =
the=20
third day it costs 80, and then the cycle repeats: on the fourth day the =
flight=20
costs 75, there is no flight on the fifth day, etc.=20
<P>The input is terminated by a scenario having <I>n</I> =3D <I>k</I> =
=3D 0.=20
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A=20
name=3DSECTION0001002000000000000000>Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2>For =
each=20
scenario in the input, first output the number of the scenario, as shown =
in the=20
sample output. If it is possible for Trisha to travel <I>k</I> days, =
starting in=20
city 1, each day flying to a different city than the day before, and =
finally=20
(after <I>k</I> days) arriving in city <I>n</I>, then print ``<TT>The =
best=20
flight costs </TT><I>x</I>.'', where <I>x</I> is the least amount that =
the=20
<I>k</I> flights can cost.=20
<P>If it is not possible to travel in such a way, print ``<TT>No flight=20
possible.</TT>''.=20
<P>Print a blank line after each scenario.=20
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A name=3DSECTION0001003000000000000000>Sample =

Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2><PRE>3 6
2 130 150
3 75 0 80
7 120 110 0 100 110 120 0
4 60 70 60 50
3 0 135 140
2 70 80
2 3
2 0 70
1 80
0 0
</PRE>
<P>
<H2><FONT color=3D#0070e8><A name=3DSECTION0001004000000000000000>Sample =

Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT> </H2><PRE>Scenario #1
The best flight costs 460.

Scenario #2
No flight possible.
</PRE>
